  <section>
    <title>Self-authenticating BACAP payload</title>
    <para>
      The first message sent (The VoucherPayload) is authenticated in
      the following manner:
    </para>
    <itemizedlist spacing="compact">
      <listitem>
        <para>
          The VoucherPayload is computed (first).
        </para>
      </listitem>
      <listitem>
        <para>
          A cryptographic hash of the VoucherPayload is computed. This
          hash <emphasis role="strong">is</emphasis> the
          <emphasis>Voucher</emphasis>*.
        </para>
      </listitem>
      <listitem>
        <para>
          The <emphasis role="strong">Voucher</emphasis> is then used to
          derive a BACAP read/write capability set.
        </para>
      </listitem>
      <listitem>
        <para>
          The VoucherPayload is uploaded to the sequence described by
          the capability (at index 0).
        </para>
      </listitem>
      <listitem>
        <para>
          Anyone who intercepts the
          <emphasis role="strong">Voucher</emphasis> can read
          <emphasis role="strong">and</emphasis> write the sequence.
        </para>
      </listitem>
      <listitem>
        <para>
          But: Since the <emphasis role="strong">Voucher</emphasis> is a
          hash over the VoucherPayload, writing the sequence with
          anything but the VoucherPayload will be detectable by the
          recipient.
        </para>
      </listitem>
      <listitem>
        <para>
          This means that the contents <emphasis>cannot</emphasis> be
          undetectably be modified by the interceptor.
        </para>
      </listitem>
    </itemizedlist>
  </section>
